{"title_page": "Asmodeus (Dutch Psychobilly band)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Asmodeus\n| image           = Asmodeus Psycho.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| landscape       = yes\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           = \n| origin          = Netherlands\n| genre           = [[Psychobilly]], [[Punkrock]]\n| years_active    = {{start date|1991}}\u2013present\n| label           =  Count Orlok, Hairball 8, Tombstone, Klub 333, Psychoholic\n| associated_acts = Barking Bulls<Br/>the Rockats<br/>Leadbeaters<br/> Casa de la Muerta\n| website         = {{URL|www.instagram.com/asmodeus.amsterdam}}\n| current_members = Arie<br/>Dim<br/>Ko\n| past_members    = Patrick Sturm<br/>Dennis Reisinger\n}}\n\n'''Asmodeus''' is a Dutch [[psychobilly]] band from [[Amsterdam]], formed in 1991.\n\n==History==\n\nAsmodeus was formed as a project in 1990 by Patrick Sturm formerly from the band the Skrunch and Ko from the also just disbanded Rockats (psychobilly).\n\nThe band is named after the [[Asmodeus]] devil. After Arie joined Patrick sang lead and played guitar. Soon after he left and pursuited a medical career in Africa. Dim was asked to join and Arie's brother Dennis took lead vocals. Bothe were in a rockabillt band tje Barking Bulls.\nThe band began recorded a demo with 4 original tracks and 2 covers. Soon after Dennis left and Arie took lead vocals for the time being. \n\nTheir first Show was in de Koog with the german formation Scum Rats. There they were immeadiately noticed by the ceo of Count Orlock records. They were invited to play at the Monsters of Rockabilly festival in Tilburg and soon after that they were signed to the Count Orlock label. In 1992 they recorded their first album Psycho on Hell's Request<ref name=Beeld>{{cite web|title=Asmodeus Biography|url=http://www.muziekencyclopedie.nl/action/entry/Asmodeus|website=Music Encyclopedia|publisher=Beeld En Geluid|accessdate=6 April 2015|language=nl}}</ref>\n\nWhat followed were many gigs in [[Switzerland]], [[West Germany]], Belgium and [[Holland]].<ref name=Beeld/>\n\nIn 1997, Asmodeus released ''Digging up the King'', again on [[Count Orlock Records]]. What followed were more shows in most European countries and the USA.\n\nIn 2005 they recorded \"Diabolique Royale\" on [[Tombstone records]]. Released in the US a couple of years later in the United States on the Texas based label, Hairball 8.\n\n[[File:Logo-asmodeus.gif|thumb]]\n\n==Side projects and other bands==\n\nBassist Arie currently plays in a Folk Americana band called the Leadbeaters. Dim today plays in a Mexicana Polka band called Casa de la Muerta. \nKo did some temporary projects in all kinds of bands, among them the Unborn Brothers and a Stray Cats cover band. He is currently doing a secret neo-rockabilly project<ref name=Beeld/>\n\n==Members==\n*Arie Reisinger \u2013 lead vocals, double bass\n*Dmitri de Jong \u2013 guitars, vocals\n*Ko Visser \u2013 drums, vocals\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n*''Psycho on Hells Request'' (Count Orlock 1993)\n*''Diggin' up the King'' (Count Orlok, 1998)\n*''Diabolique Royale'' (Tombstone records, 2005)\n\n===Compilations===\n* High Voltage, volume 1, Fiest Germany (1994)\n* Amsterdammers (1996)\n* Black Jacket Racket, Skully records (1998)\n* Kicked outta Purgatory, Psychobilly US/ Hairball 8 (2003)\n* ''[[AMP (magazine)#AMP Magazine Presents|AMP-Magazine vol 5 Psychobilly]]'' (2006)\n* God Save the King; A Psychobilly Tribute to Elvis (2005)\n* Sountrack to Oblivion, Kaiser Records (1998)\n* the Sick Ones, Flying Saucer records (2007)\n\n===Demo's===\n\n* Asmodeus, self titled (1992)\n* One of many (1997)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of psychobilly bands]]\n*[[Psychobilly]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*wiki-pychobilly[https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/psychobilly#Third_wave_internationally]\n*podiuminfo[https://www.podiuminfo.nl/artist/7724/Asmodeus/]\n*punx-nl[http://www.punx.nl/nl/bands/2/347/Asmodeus.htm]\n\n[[Category:Psychobilly groups]]\n[[Category:Dutch musical trios]]\n[[Category:Dutch rock music groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Asmodeus\n| image           = [[File:Asmodeus Psycho.jpg|thumb|Asmodeus Psycho]]\n| image_size      = \n| landscape       = yes\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| background      = group_or_band\n| alias           = \n| origin          = Netherlands\n| genre           = [[Psychobilly]], [[Punkrock]]\n| years_active    = {{start date|1991}}\u2013present\n| label           =  Count Orlok, Hairball 8, Tombstone, Klub 333, Psychoholic\n| associated_acts = Barking Bulls<Br/>the Rockats<br/>Leadbeaters<br/> Casa de la Muerta\n| website         = {{URL|www.instagram.com/asmodeus.amsterdam}}\n| current_members = Arie<br/>Dim<br/>Ko\n| past_members    = Patrick Sturm<br/>Dennis Reisinger\n}}\n\n'''Asmodeus''' is a Dutch [[psychobilly]] band from [[Amsterdam]], formed in 1991.\n\n==History==\n\nAsmodeus was formed as a project in 1990 by Patrick Sturm formerly from the band the Skrunch and Ko from the also just disbanded Rockats (psychobilly).\n\nThe band is named after the [[Asmodeus]] devil. After Arie joined Patrick sang lead and played guitar. Soon after he left and pursuited a medical career in Africa. Dim was asked to join and Arie's brother Dennis took lead vocals. Bothe were in a rockabillt band tje Barking Bulls.\nThe band began recorded a demo with 4 original tracks and 2 covers. Soon after Dennis left and Arie took lead vocals for the time being. \n\nTheir first Show was in de Koog with the german formation Scum Rats. There they were immeadiately noticed by the ceo of Count Orlock records. They were invited to play at the Monsters of Rockabilly festival in Tilburg and soon after that they were signed to the Count Orlock label. In 1992 they recorded their first album Psycho on Hell's Request<ref name=Beeld>{{cite web|title=Asmodeus Biography|url=http://www.muziekencyclopedie.nl/action/entry/Asmodeus|website=Music Encyclopedia|publisher=Beeld En Geluid|accessdate=6 April 2015|language=nl}}</ref>\n\nWhat followed were many gigs in [[Switzerland]], [[West Germany]], Belgium and [[Holland]].<ref name=Beeld/>\n\nIn 1997, Asmodeus released ''Digging up the King'', again on [[Count Orlock Records]]. What followed were more shows in most European countries and the USA.\n\nIn 2005 they recorded \"Diabolique Royale\" on [[Tombstone records]]. Released in the US a couple of years later in the United States on the Texas based label, Hairball 8.\n\n[[File:Logo-asmodeus.gif|thumb]]\n\n==Side projects and other bands==\n\nBassist Arie currently plays in a Folk Americana band called the Leadbeaters. Dim today plays in a Mexicana Polka band called Casa de la Muerta. \nKo did some temporary projects in all kinds of bands, among them the Unborn Brothers and a Stray Cats cover band. He is currently doing a secret neo-rockabilly project<ref name=Beeld/>\n\n==Members==\n*Arie Reisinger \u2013 lead vocals, double bass\n*Dmitri de Jong \u2013 guitars, vocals\n*Ko Visser \u2013 drums, vocals\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n*''Psycho on Hells Request'' (Count Orlock 1993)\n*''Diggin' up the King'' (Count Orlok, 1998)\n*''Diabolique Royale'' (Tombstone records, 2005)\n\n===Compilations===\n* High Voltage, volume 1, Fiest Germany (1994)\n* Amsterdammers (1996)\n* Black Jacket Racket, Skully records (1998)\n* Kicked outta Purgatory, Psychobilly US/ Hairball 8 (2003)\n* ''[[AMP (magazine)#AMP Magazine Presents|AMP-Magazine vol 5 Psychobilly]]'' (2006)\n* God Save the King; A Psychobilly Tribute to Elvis (2005)\n* Sountrack to Oblivion, Kaiser Records (1998)\n* the Sick Ones, Flying Saucer records (2007)\n\n===Demo's===\n\n* Asmodeus, self titled (1992)\n* One of many (1997)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of psychobilly bands]]\n*[[Psychobilly]]\n\n==External links==\n\n\n\n *wiki-pychobilly[https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/psychobilly#Third_wave_internationally]\n\n *podiuminfo[https://www.podiuminfo.nl/artist/7724/Asmodeus/]\n\n *punx-nl[http://www.punx.nl/nl/bands/2/347/Asmodeus.htm]\n\n[[:Category:Psychobilly groups]]\n[[:Category:Dutch musical trios]]\n[[:Category:Dutch rock music groups]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asmodeus_(Dutch_Psychobilly_band)"}
{"title_page": "List of the Black Crowes members", "text_new": "{{multiple image|caption_align=left|header_align=center\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 400\n| image1 = The Black Crowes Live at the Hammerstein Ballroom.jpg\n| image2 = Black crowes-Newport.jpg\n| footer = Two lineups of the Black Crowes in 2005 (top) and 2008 (bottom).\n}}\n[[The Black Crowes]] are an American [[Southern rock]] band from [[Marietta, Georgia]]. Originally formed by brothers [[Chris Robinson (singer)|Chris]] (lead vocals) and [[Rich Robinson]] (lead guitar) in 1984 as Mr Crowe's Garden, the group went through a series of early personnel changes before settling on a lineup including rhythm guitarist [[Jeff Cease]], bassist [[Johnny Colt]] and drummer [[Steve Gorman]] in 1989. The current lineup of the band, which reformed in November 2019 after breaking up for a third time in 2015, includes the Robinson brothers and new members Isaiah Mitchell (rhythm guitar), [[Tim Lefebvre]] (bass), Raj Ojha (drums) and Joel Robinow (keyboards).\n\n==History==\n===1984\u20132002===\nBrothers [[Chris Robinson (singer)|Chris]] and [[Rich Robinson]] formed Mr. Crowe's Garden in 1984, working with a succession of six bassists and three drummers during the band's formative years.<ref>{{cite book |last=Larkin |first=Colin |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |publication-date=May 27, 2011 |location=London, England |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |isbn=978-0857125958 |page=2629 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_NNmFiUnSmUC&pg=PA2629&lpg=PA2629#v=onepage&q&f=false |access-date=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> Early members included Keith Joyner (bass),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blurtonline.com/feature/time-now-time-yesterday-seven-simons/ |title=The Time Is Now, The Time Is Yesterday: Seven Simons |last=Lurie |first=Robert Dean |work=[[Blurt (magazine)|Blurt]] |date=October 28, 2016 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> Jeff Sullivan (drums),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmoremagazine.com/2016/12/reviews/films/scarred-but-smarter-life-n-times-of-drivin-n-cryin |title=Scarred But Smarter (Life N Times of Drivin N Cryin) |last=Cobb |first=Mike |work=[[Elmore Magazine]] |date=December 7, 2016 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> and Ted Selke (bass).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goldminemag.com/news/artist-news/studying-ormithology-seventh-ring-saturn |title=Studying Ormythology on the Seventh Ring of Saturn |last=Thompson |first=Dave |work=[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]] |date=June 18, 2014 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> By 1989, the group had been renamed the Black Crowes and featured rhythm guitarist [[Jeff Cease]], bassist [[Johnny Colt]] and drummer [[Steve Gorman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wpr.org/drummers-memoir-says-black-crowes-were-too-hard-handle |title=Drummer's Memoir Says Black Crowes Were 'Too Hard To Handle' |last=Friedrich |first=Adam |publisher=[[Wisconsin Public Radio]] |date=October 19, 2019 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2009/09/the-black-crowes-miserable.html |title=The Black Crowes - Miserable |work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date=September 15, 2009 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> After the release of the group's debut album ''[[Shake Your Money Maker (album)|Shake Your Money Maker]]'', Cease was replaced by former [[Burning Tree]] guitarist [[Marc Ford]] in November 1991.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-11-16-ca-1563-story.html |title=O.C. Guitarist to Join Rock's Black Crowes |last=Boehm |first=Mike |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 16, 1991 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> [[Eddie Harsch]] was added as the band's first keyboardist the following year.<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-black-crowes-mn0000048566/biography |title=The Black Crowes: Biography & History |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |author-link=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> After three more studio albums, Ford was dismissed in August 1997 due to a heroin addiction, before Colt left shortly thereafter in October.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www4.rocktropolis.com/allstar/database/news/9805/29/story3.asp |title=The Black Crowes' Chris Robinson Discusses Band's 'New Era' |last=Johnson |first=Tina |work=Allstar |date=May 29, 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980705003148/http://www4.rocktropolis.com/allstar/database/news/9805/29/story3.asp |archivedate=July 5, 1998 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nColt was replaced by [[Sven Pipien]] for ''[[By Your Side (The Black Crowes album)|By Your Side]]'', on which both lead and rhythm guitars were performed by Rich Robinson.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1425917/black-crowes-begin-work-on-new-album-name-bassist/ |title=Black Crowes Begin Work On New Album, Name Bassist |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=March 16, 1998 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> [[Audley Freed]] joined as a touring guitarist for shows starting in June 1998.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1425915/black-crowes-delay-new-album-box-set-due-in-august/ |title=Black Crowes Delay New Album, Box Set Due In August |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=July 22, 1998 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> In May 2000, Pipien was replaced by [[Greg Rzab]], debuting on a tour with former [[Led Zeppelin]] guitarist [[Jimmy Page]] following the release of ''[[Live at the Greek]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1425895/black-crowes-get-new-bassist-for-page-tour/ |title=Black Crowes Get New Bassist For Page Tour |last=Basham |first=David |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=May 10, 2000 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> Rzab had left by the end of the year, and Rich Robinson played bass on the 2001 release ''[[Lions (album)|Lions]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/78742/black-crowes-find-themselves-on-lions |title=Black Crowes Find Themselves On 'Lions' |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=April 13, 2001 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> [[Andy Hess]] took over Rzab's vacated position once the album was recorded, debuting in February 2001.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1439055/black-crowes-nest-in-ny-club-for-lions-party/ |title=Black Crowes Nest In N.Y. Club For Lions Party |last=Basham |first=David |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=February 5, 2001 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> After a final tour which spawned a live release simply titled ''[[Live (The Black Crowes album)|Live]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/live-mw0000227153 |title=Live - The Black Crowes: Songs, Reviews, Credits |last=Erlewine |first=Stephen Thomas |author-link=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> Gorman left the Black Crowes in December 2001 and the remaining members announced the band's \"indefinite hiatus\" the following month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/the-black-crowes-announce-indefinite-hiatus/ |title=The Black Crowes Announce Indefinite Hiatus |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=January 9, 2002 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===2005 onward===\nAfter a three-year hiatus, the Black Crowes reformed in March 2005 with a lineup of Chris and Rich Robinson, former members Marc Ford and Sven Pipien, and new drummer Bill Dobrow.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1497752/black-crowes-reunion-now-a-full-blown-tour/ |title=Black Crowes Reunion Now A Full-Blown Tour |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=March 4, 2005 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> Within two months, Gorman had returned as the band's drummer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/drummer-steve-gorman-rejoins-black-crowes/ |title=Drummer Steve Gorman Rejoins Black Crowes |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=May 6, 2005 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> After a tour which spawned the live release ''[[Freak 'n' Roll...Into the Fog: The Black Crowes All Join Hands, The Fillmore, San Francisco|Freak 'n' Roll... Into the Fog]]'', Harsh left in August 2006 due to \"health reasons\" and was replaced by [[Rob Clores]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/the-black-crowes-keyboardist-quits-for-health-reasons/ |title=The Black Crowes Keyboardist Quits For 'Health Reasons' |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=August 28, 2006 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> Just over a week later, Ford also left the band citing \"health reasons\", with [[Paul Stacey]] taking his place for upcoming tour dates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/guitarist-quit-black-crowes-for-health-reasons/ |title=Quitarist Quit Black Crowes For Health Reasons |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=September 8, 2006 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> Clores was dismissed and replaced by [[Adam MacDougall (musician)|Adam MacDougall]] in July 2007,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swampland.com/articles/view/title:adam_macdougall_interview_the_black_crowes_electric_spanking_of_warpaint_babies |title=Adam MacDougall Interview: The Black Crowes Electric Spanking of Warpaint Babies |last=Calemine |first=James |publisher=Swampland |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> and in November [[Luther Dickinson]] joined as second guitarist, after having performed on ''[[Warpaint (The Black Crowes album)|Warpaint]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://glidemagazine.com/140079/luther-dickinson-joins-the-black-crowes/ |title=Luther Dickinson Joins The Black Crowes |last=Bernstein |first=Scott |work=Glide |date=November 28, 2007 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> After a final tour, the band went on \"indefinite hiatus\" again in July 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/the-black-crowes-announces-final-european-leg-of-20th-anniversary-tour/ |title=The Black Crowes Announces Final European Leg Of 20th Anniversary Tour |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=January 19, 2011 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nThe Black Crowes announced its return again on [[Christmas Day]] 2012 with [[Jackie Greene]] taking Dickinson's place in the band for tour dates starting the following March.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/the-black-crowes-end-hiatus/ |title=The Black Crowes End Hiatus |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=December 25, 2012 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> The tour was followed by a period of extended inactivity before Rich Robinson formally announced in January 2015 that the Black Crowes had broken up due to a disagreement between him and brother Chris regarding ownership of the band.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/the-black-crowes-are-no-more-says-guitarist-rich-robinson/ |title=The Black Crowes Are No More, Says Guitarist Rich Robinson |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=January 15, 2015 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref> \n\nHowever, in November 2019 after several weeks of rumors, it was announced that the Black Crowes had reunited for a planned 2020 tour in commemoration of the 30th anniversary of ''Shake Your Money Maker'', with a new lineup including the Robinson brothers, rhythm guitarist Isaiah Mitchell, bassist [[Tim Lefebvre]], drummer Raj Ojha and keyboardist Joel Robinow.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/black-crowes-2020-reunion-tour-dates-910124/ |title=Black Crowes Reunite, Plot 2020 'Shake Your Money Maker' Tour |last=Blistein |first=Jon |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=November 11, 2019 |accessdate=November 12, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n===Current===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" width=100%\n|-\n!width=\"75\"|Image\n!width=\"130\"|Name\n!width=\"90\"|Years active\n!width=\"170\"|Instruments\n!Release contributions\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Chris Robinson at Kitchener Bluesfest 2018.jpg |bSize=350 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=54 |oLeft=145 }}\n|[[Chris Robinson (singer)|Chris Robinson]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{hlist|1989\u20132002|2005\u20132011|2012\u20132015|2019\u2013present}}\n|{{hlist|lead vocals|harmonica|acoustic guitar|percussion}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|all [[The Black Crowes discography|Black Crowes releases]]\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Rich Robinson (Black Crowes).jpg |bSize=315 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=50 |oLeft=95 }}\n|[[Rich Robinson]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|{{hlist|guitar|backing vocals}}\n|-\n|\n|Isaiah Mitchell\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2019\u2013present\n|guitar\n|rowspan=\"4\"|none\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Tim Lefebvre with Tedeschi Trucks Band, 2014.jpg |bSize=475 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=30 |oLeft=110 }}\n|[[Tim Lefebvre]]\n|bass\n|-\n|\n|Raj Ojha\n|{{hlist|drums|percussion}}\n|-\n|\n|Joel Robinow\n|{{hlist|keyboards|backing vocals}}\n|}\n\n===Former===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" width=100%\n|-\n!width=\"75\"|Image\n!width=\"130\"|Name\n!width=\"90\"|Years active\n!width=\"170\"|Instruments\n!Release contributions\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Steve Gorman.jpg |bSize=700 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=292 |oLeft=288 }}\n|[[Steve Gorman]]\n|{{hlist|1989\u20132001|2005\u20132011|2012\u20132015}}\n|{{hlist|drums|percussion}}\n|all Black Crowes releases to date\n|-\n|\n|[[Johnny Colt]]<br />{{small|(Charles Brandt)}}\n|1989\u20131997\n|bass\n|{{hlist|all Black Crowes releases from ''[[Shake Your Money Maker (album)|Shake Your Money Maker]]'' (1990) to ''[[Sho' Nuff Live]]'' (1998)|''[[The Lost Crowes]]'' (2006)}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Jeff Cease]]\n|1989\u20131991\n|guitar\n|''Shake Your Money Maker'' (1990)\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Marc Ford 072707.jpg |bSize=500 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=42 |oLeft=158 }}\n|[[Marc Ford]]\n|{{hlist|1991\u20131997|2005\u20132006}}\n|{{hlist|guitar|backing vocals}}\n|{{hlist|all Black Crowes releases from ''[[The Southern Harmony and Musical Companion]]'' (1992) to ''Sho' Nuff Live'' (1998)|''[[Freak 'n' Roll...Into the Fog: The Black Crowes All Join Hands, The Fillmore, San Francisco|Freak 'n' Roll... Into the Fog]]'' (2006)|''The Lost Crowes'' (2006)}}\n|-\n|\n|[[Eddie Harsch]]\n|{{hlist|1992\u20132002|2005\u20132006 {{small|(died 2016)}}}}\n|{{hlist|keyboards|piano}}\n|all Black Crowes releases from ''The Southern Harmony and Musical Companion'' (1992) to ''The Lost Crowes'' (2006)\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Steve Gorman.jpg |bSize=750 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=208 |oLeft=55 }}\n|[[Sven Pipien]]\n|{{hlist|1997\u20132000|2005\u20132011|2012\u20132015}}\n|{{hlist|bass|backing vocals}}\n|{{hlist|''[[By Your Side (The Black Crowes album)|By Your Side]]'' (1999)|''[[Live at the Greek]]'' (2000)|''Freak 'n' Roll... Into the Fog'' (2006)|all Black Crowes releases from ''[[Warpaint (The Black Crowes album)|Warpaint]]'' (2008) to ''[[Wiser for the Time]]'' (2013)}}\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Audley Freed.jpg |bSize=300 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=18 |oLeft=102 }}\n|[[Audley Freed]]\n|1998\u20132002 {{small|(initially a touring member only)}}\n|guitar\n|{{hlist|''Live at the Greek'' (2000)|''[[Lions (album)|Lions]]'' (2001)|''[[Live (The Black Crowes album)|Live]]'' (2002)}}\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Greg Rzab - Fabrik Hamburg 2017 03.jpg |bSize=500 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=57 |oLeft=195 }}\n|[[Greg Rzab]]\n|2000\n|rowspan=\"2\"|bass\n|''Live at the Greek'' (2000)\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Andy-hess DSC05131.jpg |bSize=250 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=45 |oLeft=65 }}\n|[[Andy Hess]]\n|2001\u20132002\n|''Live'' (2002)\n|-\n|\n|Bill Dobrow\n|2005\n|drums\n|rowspan=\"3\"|none {{small|\u2013 live performances only}}\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Rob Clores.jpg |bSize=275 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=48 |oLeft=122 }}\n|[[Rob Clores]]\n|2006\u20132007\n|keyboards\n|-\n|\n|[[Paul Stacey]]\n|2006\u20132007 {{small|(touring only)}}\n|guitar\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Adam MacDougall.jpg |bSize=400 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=138 |oLeft=212 }}\n|[[Adam MacDougall (musician)|Adam MacDougall]]\n|{{hlist|2007\u20132011|2012\u20132015}}\n|{{hlist|keyboards|backing vocals}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|all Black Crowes releases from ''Warpaint'' (2008) to ''Wiser for the Time'' (2013)\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Luther Dickinson-Newport.jpg |bSize=300 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=42 |oLeft=118 }}\n|[[Luther Dickinson]]\n|2007\u20132011\n|{{hlist|guitar|mandolin|harmonica}}\n|-\n|{{CSS image crop |Image=Jackie Greene 2016-02-23, The Hall at MP, Brooklyn NY.JPG |bSize=500 |cWidth=75 |cHeight=75 |oTop=44 |oLeft=175 }}\n|[[Jackie Greene]]\n|2012\u20132015\n|{{hlist|guitar|backing vocals}}\n|none {{small|\u2013 live performances only}}\n|}\n\n==Timeline==\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:100 bottom:100 top:10 right:20\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:06/01/1989 till:01/10/2020\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:4\nScaleMajor = increment:5 start:1990\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:1990\n\nColors =\n  id:lvocals value:red         legend:Lead_vocals\n  id:lguitar value:teal        legend:Lead_guitar\n  id:rguitar value:brightgreen legend:Rhythm_guitar\n  id:bass    value:blue        legend:Bass\n  id:drums   value:orange      legend:Drums\n  id:keys    value:purple      legend:Keyboards\n  id:harp    value:yellow      legend:Harmonica\n  id:bvocals value:pink        legend:Backing_vocals\n  id:spacer  value:white       legend:&nbsp;\n  id:studio  value:black       legend:Studio_album\n  id:live    value:gray(0.7)   legend:Live_recording\n  id:bars    value:gray(0.92)\n\nBackgroundColors = bars:bars\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n color:live\n  at:03/18/1995\n  at:10/18/1999\n  at:10/30/2001\n  at:08/06/2005\n  at:03/20/2008\n  at:10/31/2010\n color:studio\n  at:02/13/1990\n  at:05/12/1992\n  at:11/01/1994\n  at:07/23/1996\n  at:01/12/1999\n  at:05/07/2001\n  at:03/03/2008\n  at:09/01/2009\n  at:08/03/2010\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Chris  text:Chris Robinson\n  bar:Rich   text:Ric